Let \[f(n) = \left\{
\begin{array}{cl}
n^2-2 & \text{ if }n<0, \\
2n-20 & \text{ if }n \geq 0.
\end{array}
\right.\]What is the positive difference between the two values of $a$ that satisfy the equation $f(-2)+f(2)+f(a)=0$?

Rationale:
Multiplying the numerator and denominator by the conjugate of the denominator, we have \begin{align*}
\frac{1-i}{2+3i} \cdot \frac{2-3i}{2-3i} &= \frac{1(2) + 1(-3i) - i(2) - i(-3i)}{2(2) + 2(-3i) + 3i(2) -3i(3i)}\\
& = \frac{-1-5i}{13} \\
&= \boxed{-\frac{1}{13} - \frac{5}{13}i}.
\end{align*}

