Rationale:
The centers are at $A=(10,0)$ and $B=(-15,0)$, and the radii are 6 and 9, respectively. Since the internal tangent is shorter than the external tangent, $\overline{PQ}$ intersects  $\overline{AB}$ at a point $D$ that divides  $\overline{AB}$ into parts proportional to the radii. The right triangles $\triangle APD$ and $\triangle BQD$ are similar with ratio of similarity $2:3$. Therefore, $D=(0,0), \, PD=8,$ and $QD=12$. Thus $PQ=\boxed{20}$.

[asy]
unitsize(0.23cm);
pair Q,P,D;
Q=(-9.6,7.2);
P=(6.4,-4.8);
D=(0,0);
draw(Q--P);
draw(Circle((-15,0),9));
draw(Circle((10,0),6));
draw((-15,0)--Q--P--(10,0));
